A simple approach for this might be working with `TemporalAdjusters[1]`
Of course, there are plenty of other approaches as well ;)

Assume we create the following value object:

    class Period{
        final LocalDate begin;
        final LocalDate end;
    
        Period(LocalDate begin, LocalDate end) {
            this.begin = begin;
            this.end = end;
        }
    
        @Override
        public String toString() {
            return String.format(&quot;%s - %s&quot;, begin, end);
        }
    }

The (in this case recursive) logic might be as follows - starting with a startdate, finishdate, and an empty list - add periods as long as the finishdate is after the last periods end:

    List&lt;Period&gt; periods(LocalDate startdate, LocalDate finishdate, List&lt;Period&gt; periodsList){
            final LocalDate periodEnd = startdate.with(lastDayOfYear());
            if(periodEnd.isBefore(finishdate)){
                periodsList.add(new Period(startdate, periodEnd));
                return periods(periodEnd.plusDays(1), finishdate, periodsList);
            }
            periodsList.add(new Period(finishdate.with(firstDayOfYear()), finishdate));
            return periodsList;
        }

A complete working example with a simple main might look like this:

    import java.time.LocalDate;
    import java.util.ArrayList;
    import java.util.List;
    
    import static java.time.temporal.TemporalAdjusters.firstDayOfYear;
    import static java.time.temporal.TemporalAdjusters.lastDayOfYear;
    
    public class Periods {
    
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            final LocalDate startdate = LocalDate.parse(&quot;2022-12-01&quot;);
            final LocalDate finishdate = LocalDate.parse(&quot;2024-10-05&quot;);
    
            periods(startdate, finishdate).forEach(System.out::println);
        }
    
        private static List&lt;Period&gt; periods(LocalDate startdate, LocalDate finishdate){
            return periods(startdate, finishdate, new ArrayList&lt;&gt;());
        }
    
        private static List&lt;Period&gt; periods(LocalDate startdate, LocalDate finishdate, List&lt;Period&gt; periodsList){
            final LocalDate periodEnd = startdate.with(lastDayOfYear());
            if(periodEnd.isBefore(finishdate)){
                periodsList.add(new Period(startdate, periodEnd));
                return periods(periodEnd.plusDays(1), finishdate, periodsList);
            }
            periodsList.add(new Period(finishdate.with(firstDayOfYear()), finishdate));
            return periodsList;
        }
    
    }
    
    class Period{
        final LocalDate begin;
        final LocalDate end;
    
        Period(LocalDate begin, LocalDate end) {
            this.begin = begin;
            this.end = end;
        }
    
        @Override
        public String toString() {
            return String.format(&quot;%s - %s&quot;, begin, end);
        }
    }

As pointed out in the comments Java provides a `Period[2]` class which can be used as well. For the reason of simplicity - printing start and end - here a simple bean class is introduced.

  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/time/temporal/TemporalAdjusters.html
  [2]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/time/Period.html

